We can use the binomial probability formula, which states that the probability of $k$ successes in $n$ trials, where each trial has a probability $p$ of success, is

$$P(k)={n\choose k}p^k(1-p)^{n-k}.$$In this case, we have $n=7$ trials (islands), $k=4$ successes (islands with treasure), and $p=\frac{1}{5}$ (the probability of an island having treasure).  Therefore, the probability that exactly 4 of the islands have treasure is

\begin{align*}
P(4)&={7\choose 4}\left(\frac{1}{5}\right)^4\left(1-\frac{1}{5}\right)^{7-4}\\
&={7\choose 4}\left(\frac{1}{5}\right)^4\left(\frac{4}{5}\right)^3\\
&=\boxed{\frac{56}{625}}
\end{align*}
